{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"4868417046c2c9e2398da7c87492e4e2e61eb7eeb395f1b4ec0396308407b307","slug":"pages.m08-introduction-to-probability-5-of-5","location":"/pages/094-m08-introduction-to-probability-5-of-5.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Introduction to Probability (5 of 5)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"094-m08-introduction-to-probability-5-of-5.md","url":"/build/094-m08-introduction-903eac46c5e471fd865bf15af66c89b3.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Learning Objectives","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"CLiM5L9MO7"}],"key":"Fco1qw2YXq"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"- Relate the probability of an event to the likelihood of this event occurring.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"tr2JgQII6N"}],"key":"SxlffHnoQn"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We will now shift our discussion to empirical ways to determine probabilities.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"c52Cltkjn3"}],"key":"gmabLfRD7d"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A Question","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"TlmMOes8RC"}],"identifier":"a-question","label":"A Question","html_id":"a-question","implicit":true,"key":"Tphq3JW4dO"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A single flip of a coin has an uncertain outcome. So, every time a coin is flipped, the outcome of that flip is unknown until the flip occurs.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"KcgiMT4hJy"}],"key":"k3B85eQVeb"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"However, if you flip a fair coin over and over again, would you expect P(H) to be exactly 0.5?","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"M9ZHqI2bpO"}],"key":"h4kwUbsHBf"},{"type":"text","value":" In other words, would you expect there to be the same number of results of “heads” as there are “tails”?","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"zS0t1VHHxU"}],"key":"ew47uH63P6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The following activity will allow you to discover the answer.","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"lJ61J7UOHX"}],"key":"bxOWKD1HM2"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"ZILVJfVC86"}],"key":"UFLyvRsKff"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Learn By Doing**\n\nIntroduction (Probability)\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"UeFzeKsjBF"}],"key":"Pkxp0mHVKe"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The above Learn by Doing activity was our first example of the second way of determining probability: Empirical (Observational) methods. In the activity, we determined that the probability of getting the result “heads” is 0.5 by flipping a fair coin many, many times.","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"key":"rvgW1Wrffd"}],"key":"jLKkkud5dM"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A Second Question","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"BAecprK5qJ"}],"identifier":"a-second-question","label":"A Second Question","html_id":"a-second-question","implicit":true,"key":"KxAsAYI4Cq"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"After doing this experiment, an important question naturally comes to mind. ","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"tAYLKlQDfg"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How would we know if the coin was not fair?","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"y6mXYA793N"}],"key":"GeMLwjcdwn"},{"type":"text","value":" Certainly, classical probability methods would never be able to answer this question. In addition, classical methods could never tell us the actual P(H). The only way to answer this question is to perform another experiment.","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"WiG4aROYjs"}],"key":"IhfzmE5Cp0"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The next activity will allow you to do just that.","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"key":"UOmjnPEKPu"}],"key":"eVj329YGPn"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"TU8NF4Rgk4"}],"key":"UYR34px1IW"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Learn By Doing**\n\nIntroduction (Probability)\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"key":"TlMeLQIOzG"}],"key":"uVIC6MREFB"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So, these types of experiments can verify classical probabilities and they can also determine when games of chance are not following ","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"CcLPzLsLPD"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"fair","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"So2FXaG6ZP"}],"key":"oSQiYkU9Oc"},{"type":"text","value":" practices. However, their real importance is to answer probability questions that arise when we are faced with a situation that does not follow any pattern and cannot be predetermined. In reality, most of the probabilities of interest to us fit the latter description.","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"kVzALPkj7i"}],"key":"vnOBiAGexn"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"To Summarize","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"a8kIQoDoT4"}],"identifier":"to-summarize","label":"To Summarize","html_id":"to-summarize","implicit":true,"key":"YLYsycQ4VG"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"1.","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"frVpTYS13J"}],"key":"Xlhb3uCq2N"},{"type":"text","value":" Probability is a way of quantifying uncertainty.","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"o3N2im1mGi"}],"key":"gVforkETPe"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"2.","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"wpvrxhaymI"}],"key":"bImJKIvAml"},{"type":"text","value":" We are interested in the probability of an event—the likelihood of the event occurring.","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"lTNb9A2kmk"}],"key":"qi4r38QzJp"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"3.","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"b1TLmDdViP"}],"key":"oLP5w1d6xr"},{"type":"text","value":" The probability of an event ranges from 0 to 1. The closer the probability is to 0, the less likely the event is to occur. The closer the probability is to 1, the more likely the event is to occur.","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"Dn6AwAwMtC"}],"key":"BVySHCVAWw"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"4.","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"Gaad6zaffS"}],"key":"PTMBnUVwdI"},{"type":"text","value":" There are two ways to determine probability: Theoretical (Classical) and Empirical (Observational).","position":{"start":{"line":51,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"key":"hSxzGlwH9x"}],"key":"Kgq0zjghkd"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"5.","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"wKDsiAYqG7"}],"key":"XnBCu9tCLh"},{"type":"text","value":" Theoretical methods use the nature of the situation to determine probabilities.","position":{"start":{"line":53,"column":1},"end":{"line":53,"column":1}},"key":"nttlR1e5kH"}],"key":"nAK5cohyS2"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"6.","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"key":"zjP7qLwWlL"}],"key":"QjU2oy3737"},{"type":"text","value":" Empirical methods use a series of trials that produce outcomes that cannot be predicted in advance (hence the uncertainty).","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"key":"KjOw8Gcr1f"}],"key":"FXdAahgvmN"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"rv9A2axIpq"}],"key":"KIB4GRF5A0"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**My Response**\n\nAbout Probability\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"key":"VIVXDh76v9"}],"key":"JwcuV8pIEk"}],"key":"xNjf6O7p0a"}],"key":"njFNsgLbQM"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"pr